### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

- `@angular/core`

### Description

## Summary

- In common situations about ControlValueAccessor, `input()` and `model()` are not useful too.
- I think the missing piece is the `transform` option of the `model()` function.

Please consider a custom checkbox scenario like below. The component has `disabled` input which can set by three ways: 1. HTML-standard style `<app-checkbox disabled>`, 2. Simple property-binding `<app-checkbox [disabled]="true">` and 3. via form control `disable()` method.

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  standalone: true,
  imports: [AppCheckbox, ReactiveFormsModule],
  template: `
    <app-checkbox disabled />
    <app-checkbox [disabled]="true" />
    <app-checkbox [formControl]="formControl" />
  `,
})
export class App {
  formControl = new FormControl(false);

  constructor() {
    this.formControl.disable();
  }
}
```

Quite simply, that functionality cannot be achieved with Signal APIs at the same time. 

With `input()` function, the `disabled` property becomes a read-only signal within the component. So `setDisabledState()` cannot set a value from the form control. 

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-checkbox',
})
export class AppCheckbox {
  disabled = input(false, { transform: booleanAttribute });

  setDisabledState(isDisabled: boolean) {
    this.disabled.set(isDisabled); // <--- input() is read-only
  }
}
``` 

On the other hand, with `model()` function cannot take the `transform` option. So `<app-checkbox disabled>` doesn't work.

```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-checkbox',
})
export class AppCheckbox {
  disabled = model(false, { transform: booleanAttribute }); // <-- model doesn't have `transform`

  setDisabledState(isDisabled: boolean) {
    this.disabled.set(isDisabled);
  }
}
```

Unfortunately, there was an issue proposed in the past regarding a similar problem, but it was closed by implementing the `model()` function. However, it does not cover the existing CVA use cases.

- https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/53889

### Proposed solution

Making the `model()` function to accept the `transform` option.

### Alternatives considered

Or, adding a completely new method for use cases such as `ControlValueAccessor`.

